      "question": "Assertion (A): If $\\theta$ is an acute angle and $\\sin \\theta = \\cos \\theta$, then the value of $\\tan \\theta$ is $1$. \\nReason (R): For any angle $\\theta$ in a right-angled triangle, $\\tan \\theta = \\frac{\\sin \\theta}{\\cos \\theta}$.",
      "answer": "(A)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Check the Assertion: Given $\\sin \\theta = \\cos \\theta$. Dividing by $\\cos \\theta$ (since $\\theta$ is acute, $\\cos \\theta \\neq 0$), we get $\\frac{\\sin \\theta}{\\cos \\theta} = 1$, which implies $\\tan \\theta = 1$. Thus, Assertion is true.",
          "Check the Reason: The definition of the tangent ratio in a right triangle is indeed the ratio of the sine of the angle to the cosine of the angle, $\\tan \\theta = \\frac{\\sin \\theta}{\\cos \\theta}$. Thus, Reason is true.",
          "Conclusion: The Reason correctly provides the mathematical definition used to derive the value in the Assertion."
        ],
        "derivation": "$\\sin \\theta = \\cos \\theta \\Rightarrow \\frac{\\sin \\theta}{\\cos \\theta} = 1 \\Rightarrow \\tan \\theta = 1 \\\\ \\text{Definition: } \\tan \\theta = \\frac{\\text{opposite}}{\\text{adjacent}} = \\frac{\\text{opposite}/\\text{hypotenuse}}{\\text{adjacent}/\\text{hypotenuse}} = \\frac{\\sin \\theta}{\\cos \\theta}$"
      },
